Name: Host-parasite web
Description: Undirected, weighted, bipartite adjacency network of Canadian freshwater fish (hosts) and their metazoan parasites (parasites). The name of the lake to which this dataset corresponds is the first word of the dataset (text prior to the underscore). Network is formatted as an edgelist. Node labels (words) were provided in the raw dataset, which can be found at the source URL (below). On the webpage at the source URL (below), select the appropriate named link under the "Data files" heading.

Name: Amazon co-purchasing network
Description: Directed, unweighted network of items for sale on amazon.com in June 2003 and the items they recommend (via the Customers Who Bought This Item Also Bought feature). If one item is frequently co-purchased with another, then the first item recommends the second.
Citation: Leskovec J, Adamic L, Adamic B. The Dynamics of Viral Marketing. ACM Transactions on the Web (ACM TWEB). 2007; 1.

Name: CAIDA AS graph
Description: Directed, weighted network snapshot denoting Autonomous System (AS) relationships on the Internet, from 2004-2007, inferred using the Serial-1 method from RouteViews BGP table snapshots and a set of heuristics.
Citation: The CAIDA AS Relationships Dataset 2007. URL http://www.caida.org/data/as-relationships.

Name: Kaggle Chess Players
Description: A directed, signed network (edgelist) among chess players (nodes) giving the chess match outcomes (edges), for game-by-game results among the world's top chess players. The direction of edge (i,j) denotes white player (i) and black player (j). Each edge is timestamped (approximate). Edge sign is +1 for a win by white, 0 for draw, and -1 for a win by black. The dataset is anonymous: the identity of the players in unknown and timestamps are approximate. Column 1 is ID of white player; column 2 is ID of black player; column 3 is result of the game (+1 for white win, 0 for draw, -1 for black win); column 4 is timestamp to one month precision.
Citation: Chess ratings- Elo versus the Rest of the World. Kaggle (2010).

Name: Human gene-disease network
Description: Undirected, unweighted, bipartite network of associations between human diseases and human genes, as extracted from the Morbid Map (MM) of the Online Mendelian Inheritance in Man (OMIM).
Citation: Goh K, Cusick M, Valle D, Childs B, Vidal M, Barabasi A. The human disease network. Proc Natl Acad Sci. 2007; 104(21): 8685-8690.

Name: Human gene-disease network
Description: Undirected, weighted network based on the bipartite `diseasome` dataset also provided in ICON. This network does not include genes as nodes. Instead, diseases are included as nodes, diseases that share connections to genes in `diseasome` are connected by an edge, whose weight is equal to the number of genes shared by the two diseases.
Citation: Goh K, Cusick M, Valle D, Childs B, Vidal M, Barabasi A. The human disease network. Proc Natl Acad Sci. 2007; 104(21): 8685-8690.

Name: Internet Routers
Description: Undirected, unweighted network that is a symmetrized snapshot of the structure of the Internet at the level of autonomous systems, reconstructed from BGP tables posted by the University of Oregon Route Views Project at <http://routeviews.org>. This was created by Mark Newman in 2006. Network is formatted as an edgelist. Each node is also associated with numerical labels - these have been omitted from the dataset loaded by this R pacakge. However, this information can be found in the raw dataset at this package's GitHub repo at <https://github.com/rrrlw/ICON> under the "data-raw" directory. On the webpage at the source URL (below), download the linked GML file under the "Web and Internet" heading associated with the bullet point titled "Internet".
Citation: Newman M. Internet (2006). University of Oregon Route Views Project. <http://routeviews.org>

Name: Karate Club
Description: Undirected, unweighted social network of friendships between 34 members of a karate club at a U.S. univesity in the 1970s. Network is formatted as an edgelist. Node labels were not provided in the raw dataset, which can be found at this package's GitHub repo at <https://github.com/rrrlw/ICON> under the "data-raw" directory. On the webpage at the source URL (below), download the linked GML file under the "Social Networks" heading associated with the bullet point titled "Zachary's Karate Club".
Citation: Zachary WW. An information flow model for conflict and fission in small groups. Journal of Anthropological Research. 1977; 33: 452-473.

Name: Coauthorships in Network Science
Description: Undirected, weighted coauthorship network of scientists working on network theory, compiled by M. Newman in May 2006. Network is formatted as an edgelist. See the cited journal article below to understand how edge weight was calculated. Each node is also associated with researcher names - these have been omitted from the dataset loaded by this R pacakge. However, this information can be found in the raw dataset at this package's GitHub repo at <https://github.com/rrrlw/ICON> under the "data-raw" directory. On the webpage at the source URL, download the linked GML file under the "Social Networks" heading associated with the bullet point titled "Coauthorships in network science".
Citation: Newman MEJ. Finding community structure in networks using the eigenvectors of matrices. Phys Rev E. 2006; 74: 036104.

Name: C. elegans neurons
Description: Directed, weighted network representing neural connections of the Caenorhabditis elegans nematode.
Citation: White JG, Southgate E, Thompson JN, Brenner S. The structure of the nervous system of the nematode C. elegans. Phil. Trans. R. Soc. London. 1986; 314: 1-340.

Name: Plant-pollinator web
Description: Undirected, unweighted, bipartite network of plants and pollinators from a single elevation in the Andean (alpine) zone on the Cordon del Crepo in central Chile.
Citation: Arroyo MTK, Primack RB, Armesto JJ. Community studies in pollination ecology in the high temperate Andes of Central Chile. I. Pollination mechanisms and altitudinal variation. American Journal of Botany. 1982; 69: 82-97.

Name: Plant-pollinator web
Description: Undirected, weighted, bipartite network of plants and pollinators from the boreal forest of central New Brunswick, Canada, as collected from May to September of 1978, 1979, and 1980. Edge weights represent interaction frequency.
Citation: Barrett SCH, Helenurm K. The reproductive-biology of boreal forest herbs. 1. Breeding systems and pollination. Canadian Journal of Botany. 1987; 65: 2036-2046.

Name: Plant-ant web
Description: Undirected, weighted, bipartite network of plants and ant species, from the rainforest at the Australian Canopy Crane in Cape Tribulation, Australia. Edge weights represent the frequency of species interaction and includes abundance estimates on the nodes.
Citation: Bluthgen N, Stork NE, Fiedler K. Bottom-up control and co-occurrence in complex communities: Honeydew and nectar determine a rainforest ant mosaic. Oikos. 2004; 106: 344-358.

Name: Power grid
Description: Undirected, unweighted network representing topology of the Western States Power Grid of the United States. Data compiled by D. Watts and S. Strogatz. Network is formatted as an edgelist. Node labels were not provided in the raw dataset, which can be found at this package's GitHub repo at <https://github.com/rrrlw/ICON> under the "data-raw" directory. On the webpage at the source URL (below), download the linked GML file under the "Infrastructure Networks" heading associated with the bullet point titled "Power grid".
Citation: Watts DJ, Strogatz SH. Collective dynamics of small-world networks. Nature. 1998; 393: 440-442.

Name: Binary Interactome
Description: Undirected, unweighted network of S. cerevisiae protein-protein interactions extracted by combining results of high-throughput yeast two-hybrid experiments and literature curation of known interactions.
Citation: Das J, Yu H. HINT: High-quality protein interactomes and their applications in understanding human disease. BMC Systems Biology. 2012; 6(1): 92.

Name: Yeast Interactome
Description: Undirected, unweighted network of protein-protein interactions in Saccharamyces cerevisiae (budding yeast), measured by co-complex associations identified by high-throughput affinity purification and mass spectrometry (AP/MS). Network is formatted as an edgelist. On the webpage at the source URL, select the "Combined-AP/MS" link to download the original, raw dataset. Both columns contain one of the proteins part of the protein-protein interaction.
Citation: Collins SR, Kemmeren P, Zhao XC, et al. Toward a comprehensive atlas of the physical interactome of Saccharomyces cerevisiae. Mol Cell Proteomics. 2007; 6(3): 439-450.

Name: Seed-disperser web
Description: A bipartite network of bird and plant interactions. Data was recorded by counting number of visits of each bird species to each plant species. The original data format (interaction frequency matrix) has been converted to an edgelist of interaction counts. Of note, pairs with zero interactions have been omitted. As a result, a small subset of birds and plants that were in the original matrix are not present in this dataset (i.e. birds that did not interact with any plants and vice versa). Additionally, only the common names of the bird and plant species are included. For the scientific names (genus and species), please see the original data source (link below). Column 1 is the common name of the bird species; column 2 is the common name of the plant species; column 3 is the number of times the bird was observed to interact with the plant.
Citation: Snow BK, Snow DW (1988). Birds and Berries. Calton, England.

Name: Seed-disperser web
Description: A bipartite network of birds and plants from a forest on Mount Missim (Papua New Guinea) collected between July 1978 to November 1980. Edge weights represent the frequency of interaction between a bird and a plant.
Citation: Beehler B. Frugivory and polygamy in birds of paradise. The Auk. 1983; 100: 1-12.

Name: Host-parasite web
Description: Undirected, weighted, bipartite adjacency network of Canadian freshwater fish (hosts) and their metazoan parasites (parasites). The name of the lake to which this dataset corresponds is the first word of the dataset (text prior to the underscore). Network is formatted as an edgelist. Node labels (words) were provided in the raw dataset, which can be found at the source URL (below). On the webpage at the source URL (below), select the appropriate named link under the "Data files" heading.

Name: Terrorist network
Description: Undirected, unweighted adjacency network of terrorists. Network is formatted as an edgelist. Node labels (names) were provided in the raw dataset, which can be found at the ICON database. On the webpage at the source URL (below), download the linked folder under the "Terrorist associations" heading (4th in list).
Citation: Krebs V. Mapping networks of terrorist cells. Connections. 2002; 24: 43-52.

Name: Word adjacencies
Description: Undirected, unweighted adjacency network of common adjectives and nouns in the novel David Copperfield by Charles Dickens. Network is formatted as an edgelist. Node labels (words) were provided in the raw dataset, which can be found at this package's GitHub repo at <https://github.com/rrrlw/ICON> under the "data-raw" directory. On the webpage at the source URL (below), download the linked GML file under the "Other Networks" heading associated with the bullet point titled "Word adjacencies".
Citation: Newman MEJ. Finding community structure in networks using the eigenvectors of matrices. Phys Rev E. 2006; 74: 036104.

Name: Word adjacencies
Description: Directed, unweighted adjacency network of words in the English language (Darwin book). Network is formatted as an edgelist. Node labels (words) were not provided in the raw dataset, which can be found at this package's GitHub repo at <https://github.com/rrrlw/ICON> under the "data-raw" directory. On the webpage at the source URL (below), download the linked TXT file under the "Languages: word adjacency networks" bullet point.
